In probability theory, the probability of two events occurring together (a conjunction) is always less than or equal to the probability of either one occurring alone - formally, for two events A and B, P(A and B) ≤ P(A) and P(A and B) ≤ P(B).

Therefore, the probability of Jasper playing fetch with his dog and having the specific goal of improving his own running speed is always less than or equal to the probability of him simply playing fetch with his dog.
